This disposes of the otherwise possible interpretation of civitas as a tribe (Peter) or canton (John). Favorabilis is a post-Augustan word, first found in Vell. II 34, 2. Here it is used in a passive sense ‘favored, popular.' Nipp. Ann. II 36 insists that favorabilis always signifies ‘was Beifall erregt.' However true this may be for the majority of instances‚ such a translation is utterly inapplicable to ‘civitas' in any of the possible meanings of the word.
